description:
Launched by Polystyle the week of 14th April 1978, Target was a weekly title intended as a companion comic to Polystyle's established TV Comic, aimed at a slightly older demographic, harkening on its cover by name back to Polystyle's defunct TV Action. Its strips were all based on crime-busting TV shows.

Target, the comic's title strip, was a BBC1 police drama set in Southampton and starring Patrick Mower as Detective Superintendent Steve Hackett; intended as a counterpart to ITV's successful Sweeney, it was between its first and second seasons on TV when the comic was released, and the TV show was already struggling for survival, not an auspicious sign for the comic.

Hazell was ITV's cockney private detective James Hazell, played by Nicholas Ball, whose first series had just finished airing a couple of weeks before Target hit the shops.

Charlie's Angels was based on the ABC TV show, Kojak covered the adventures of Telly Savalas' famous detective, while Cannon, about William Conrad's LA detective Frank Cannon, was a reprint of the strip that had originally appeared in TV Action.

With low production values and frankly uninspiring covers, Target's days were numbered almost from the outset, and it was cancelled with its 19th issue on the week of 18th August 1978. The cover hinted to readers of this demise with a note "Exciting news inside", a sure sign to any knowledgeable reader that the title they had been faithfully collecting was being terminated and merged into another more successful sibling, in this case TV Comic.
name: Target

description:
A weekly adventure title launched by Fleetway, with the first issue cover dated 4th May 1968, Jag stood out from most other comics on sale in British newagents due to its larger, tabloid-sized pages and better quality paper, with additional colour pages. However, this also led to a higher price, with Jag being twice as expensive as many of its contemporaries. In February 1969 Jag's page size was reduced while its page count was increased, presumably an effort to make it more appealing to potential buyers, but despite this Jag was cancelled the next month, the last issue dated 29th March 1969, and merged into Tiger a week later.

Numbering note: Apart from the first couple of issues, Jag was not numbered. As such, the numbers below reflect year (minus the century, as all are 1900s), month and date of publication.
name: Jag

description:
Having appeared previously in Pow! Annuals and one TV21 Annual, Spider-Man finally headlined his own U.K. annual in 1974. Initially published by Grandreams in conjunction with Marvel UK, the annuals reprinted US Spider-Man tales from various different Spidey titles, alongside features and games. In the 1980s new illustrated text stories were also included in several annuals. The annuals skipped 1987 and 1988, then stopped after 1993 for a few more years, before returning in 1996 and 1997, hoping the extra interest generated by the UK showing of the 1994 Spider-Man cartoon would boost sales.

The annuals then took a break again until 2002, when the Tobey Maguire Spider-Man movie came out, again raising public interest in the character. Since then there has been a Spider-Man Annual each year, published by Marvel's current UK license holder, Panini; the 2007 annual (cover dated 2008) was renamed as Spider-Man 3 Annual, to tie in with the third Maguire movie's release, but the name reverted back a year later.
name: Spider-Man Annual

The new title began in October 2011, immediately after the final issue of Spider-Man and Friends was published. It is released every four weeks
name: Marvel Super Hero Squad Magazine

description:
Spider-Man and Friends was a pre-schooler title published in Britain by Panini, tying in with the toy line of the same name. It was released every four weeks, and each issue came with a free gift sellotaped to the cover, with activities, games and a brand new, UK-written and drawn comic strip inside the comic, featuring the adventures of a Mangaesque Spider-Man and his school friends, including his cousin Spider-Girl, Captain America, Hulk, Doc Ock and Lizard. The first issue was released in October 2006, but in 2011 Marvel decided to stop all non-US titles from publishing new material. As a result, Spider-Man and Friends was cancelled after 66 issues, the final one dated October 2011; that same month Panini began a replacement title, Marvel Super Hero Squad Magazine, tying in with the cartoon of that name, and reprinting the US Marvel Super Hero Squad comic.

There was a single Spider-Man and Friends Annual published in 2008.
name: Spider-Man and Friends

High, Primeval and Merlin. Each issue includes posters, puzzles, free gifts and, with the exception of the first Merlin issue (#4), original comic strips, all featuring that issue's chosen topic.
name: Totally...
